

Texas Instruments is selling its software division for 165 million dollars in cash to Sterling Software of Dallas, Texas, the two firms reported Monday.

The transaction includes the sale of all Texas Instruments Software assets, including the stock of certain European subsidiaries, and the assumption of various liabilities related to the business.

Sterling Software expects to merge this business with its existing applications development business upon completion of the purchase, which is expected to be in mid June, Texas Instruments said.

The software of the computer and semiconductor maker has operations in 30 countries around the world.

Sterling Software produces software and services for applications management and systems management, as well as technical professional services for the US government.

In 1996 Sterling Software reported revenue of 439.2 million dollars. Texas Instruments Software reported revenue of about 250 million last year.

